And it's really what
I am at this point,

00:00:18.720 --> 00:00:21.500
well, beyond going out
to catch my own dinner,

00:00:21.500 --> 00:00:23.680
I am a fishmonger.

00:00:23.680 --> 00:00:25.460
I have to accept that
that's what I am.

00:00:25.460 --> 00:00:27.900
I'm a fisherman too, but
I'm mostly a fish monger.

00:00:30.600 --> 00:00:34.360
This book, however, is about
how to catch your own fish.

00:00:34.360 --> 00:00:37.012
But there's a lot of
songs about fisherman,

00:00:37.012 --> 00:00:39.220
but there's only like two
or three about fishmongers.

00:00:39.220 --> 00:00:39.890
So here's one.

00:00:43.260 --> 00:00:45.420
[SINGING "MOLLY MALONE"]

00:02:46.363 --> 00:02:48.710
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:48.710 --> 00:02:51.130
You see, the real
reason that we do

00:02:51.130 --> 00:02:54.180
that is just it loosens
me up, and then it's

00:02:54.180 --> 00:02:56.550
kind of nice to
start with clapping.

00:02:56.550 --> 00:03:00.830
Whether I end with clapping
or not is a whole other issue.

00:03:00.830 --> 00:03:03.380
Well here's my book.

00:03:03.380 --> 00:03:07.650
And I'm supposed to talk
about my book today.

00:03:07.650 --> 00:03:12.814
And run a business
called Sea Forager.

00:03:12.814 --> 00:03:14.230
Many of you may
know this already,

00:03:14.230 --> 00:03:17.340
but I'm just going to
backtrack a little bit.

00:03:17.340 --> 00:03:20.980
And Sea Forager
is the culmination

00:03:20.980 --> 00:03:24.180
of sort of my crazy
misspent life walking

00:03:24.180 --> 00:03:25.940
the intertidal
zone of this area.

00:03:25.940 --> 00:03:28.080
The intertidal zone
is a fancy term

00:03:28.080 --> 00:03:30.950
for that area between
high tide and low tide.

00:03:30.950 --> 00:03:34.030
That's kind of my zone.

00:03:34.030 --> 00:03:37.850
There's a famous book about the
intertidal zone of California

00:03:37.850 --> 00:03:41.406
called "Between Pacific Tides."

00:03:41.406 --> 00:03:43.280
Raise your hand if you've
heard of this book?

00:03:43.280 --> 00:03:44.404
Oh great, that's excellent.

00:03:44.404 --> 00:03:51.330
It just makes me feel smarter
than you, or more nerdy,

00:03:51.330 --> 00:03:53.940
really.

00:03:53.940 --> 00:03:57.760
"Between Pacific Tides"
was written by a biologist

00:03:57.760 --> 00:04:00.830
by the name of Doc
or Ed Ricketts.

00:04:00.830 --> 00:04:03.350
Ed Ricketts was the
central character

00:04:03.350 --> 00:04:07.630
in Steinbeck's "Cannery Row,"
and was also Steinbeck's best

00:04:07.630 --> 00:04:09.650
friend, John
Steinbeck's best friend.

00:04:09.650 --> 00:04:11.570
And they wrote a
little book called

00:04:11.570 --> 00:04:13.930
"The Log Book of
the Sea of Cortez,"

00:04:13.930 --> 00:04:16.660
which is a wonderful
sort of travelogue

00:04:16.660 --> 00:04:20.637
of their experiences
in the intertidal zone,

00:04:20.637 --> 00:04:23.220
that area between high tide and
low tide, along the California

00:04:23.220 --> 00:04:25.140
coast all the way down to Baja.

00:04:25.140 --> 00:04:29.390
And it's kind of a cool place.

00:04:29.390 --> 00:04:34.240
I didn't actually mean
to do this, but why not?

00:04:34.240 --> 00:04:38.890
That book, "Between Pacific
Tides," sort of made

00:04:38.890 --> 00:04:42.100
the California intertidal zone,
put it on the map, so to speak.

00:04:44.690 --> 00:04:46.620
It's sort of a tome
of marine biology.

00:04:46.620 --> 00:04:50.540
So if you go to Humboldt
State or wherever,

00:04:50.540 --> 00:04:53.130
you can get a good
degree in marine biology,

00:04:53.130 --> 00:04:55.690
and you'll know all about
"Between Pacific Tides."

00:04:55.690 --> 00:04:59.900
And if you get a first
edition copy of that book,

00:04:59.900 --> 00:05:03.930
you'll notice it looks-- sort
of the aesthetic of the cover

00:05:03.930 --> 00:05:06.120
is not dissimilar to this.

00:05:06.120 --> 00:05:08.230
And that's not an accident.

00:05:08.230 --> 00:05:11.790
My book is a foraging
and fishing guide.

00:05:11.790 --> 00:05:14.730
It is not a textbook
of marine biology.

00:05:14.730 --> 00:05:17.700
This is filled with
humorous haikus and poems

00:05:17.700 --> 00:05:24.390
and funny anecdotes about
some of the strange things

00:05:24.390 --> 00:05:27.810
that I've eaten and
hunted on the shoreline.

00:05:27.810 --> 00:05:31.680
In other words, it's
not a piece of science.

00:05:31.680 --> 00:05:33.920
And yet there's some good
scientific data in here,

00:05:33.920 --> 00:05:37.180
if you are interested in that.

00:05:37.180 --> 00:05:39.780
But I was so influenced by that
book "Between Pacific Tides"

00:05:39.780 --> 00:05:43.320
and by its writer,
Doc Ricketts, who's

00:05:43.320 --> 00:05:48.660
one of the great eccentrics
of the California shores.

00:05:48.660 --> 00:05:51.050
He tragically died at
the age of, I think,

00:05:51.050 --> 00:05:53.430
38 or something, so very young.

00:05:53.430 --> 00:05:56.800
He was hit by a train.

00:05:56.800 --> 00:06:00.920
And it took him three days
to die after getting run over

00:06:00.920 --> 00:06:02.180
by a train.

00:06:02.180 --> 00:06:08.110
And John Steinbeck
said rather famously--

00:06:08.110 --> 00:06:10.020
they were like best
friends, inseparable.

00:06:10.020 --> 00:06:11.830
And Steinbeck, who
was just heartbroken

00:06:11.830 --> 00:06:15.500
by this, he said, "Well,
the only thing that could

00:06:15.500 --> 00:06:19.190
have killed Ed was a train.

00:06:19.190 --> 00:06:21.460
And it took three days at that."

00:06:21.460 --> 00:06:27.530
In any case, when I got my
buddy Leighton to do all the art

00:06:27.530 --> 00:06:28.290
work.

00:06:28.290 --> 00:06:30.810
And if you just look through
this, and you kind of just,

00:06:30.810 --> 00:06:33.850
boop, boop, boop,
I think you'll see

00:06:33.850 --> 00:06:37.200
that the detail and sort
of the humor come through.

00:06:37.200 --> 00:06:40.420
So if you look at the
[INAUDIBLE] page on page 85,

00:06:40.420 --> 00:06:42.210
you'll see that the
thing that he always

00:06:42.210 --> 00:06:44.310
puts in the background
of an image,

00:06:44.310 --> 00:06:48.030
so that you can see the size,
is some form of detritus

00:06:48.030 --> 00:06:50.360
from our American civilization.

00:06:50.360 --> 00:06:54.530
So if you look in
the bait section,

00:06:54.530 --> 00:07:00.320
you'll see under the--
innkeeper warm on 81, a rather

00:07:00.320 --> 00:07:02.272
adult illustration.

00:07:05.510 --> 00:07:07.370
Yeah, because the
fat innkeeper one

00:07:07.370 --> 00:07:10.670
is also called the penis
fish, by various cultures.

00:07:10.670 --> 00:07:15.770
And, well, you can see that
there is a spent condom wrapper

00:07:15.770 --> 00:07:19.180
there to illustrate the size.

00:07:19.180 --> 00:07:21.040
And then if you
look at page 168--

00:07:21.040 --> 00:07:24.400
I just thumbed through there--
we were singing about cockles

00:07:24.400 --> 00:07:26.847
and mussels, and we got all
kinds of cockles and mussels

00:07:26.847 --> 00:07:28.930
in this book if you're
interested in those things.

00:07:28.930 --> 00:07:30.946
We have cockles in California.

00:07:30.946 --> 00:07:32.820
There's cockles that
everybody calls cockles,

00:07:32.820 --> 00:07:34.750
and then there's real cockles.

00:07:34.750 --> 00:07:35.840
We talk about that later.

00:07:35.840 --> 00:07:37.530
But if you look on
page 168, you'll

00:07:37.530 --> 00:07:42.160
see the size of the thing
that he put for scale here

00:07:42.160 --> 00:07:44.370
is a cigarette butt.

00:07:44.370 --> 00:07:48.140
So I wanted it to sort of
have this feeling of being

00:07:48.140 --> 00:07:49.442
part of the modern world.

00:07:49.442 --> 00:07:51.150
And that's how Leighton
chose to do that.

00:07:51.150 --> 00:07:54.015
But Leighton, the
illustrator of this book,

00:07:54.015 --> 00:07:55.640
is just somebody I've
known a long time

00:07:55.640 --> 00:07:57.720
and I've just always
loved his little drawings,

00:07:57.720 --> 00:08:00.340
and I wanted to
collaborate with him.

00:08:00.340 --> 00:08:03.800
And so the publisher, when
they saw a few of his drawings,

00:08:03.800 --> 00:08:05.910
they immediately hired
him on, and paid him

00:08:05.910 --> 00:08:07.560
to do all of the illustrations.

00:08:07.560 --> 00:08:09.610
But he didn't just want
to do illustrations.

00:08:09.610 --> 00:08:12.360
He wanted to have a hand
in the design of the book.

00:08:12.360 --> 00:08:14.150
And so he called me
one day, after he had

00:08:14.150 --> 00:08:16.364
been hired on to the project.

00:08:16.364 --> 00:08:17.530
And we were both very happy.

00:08:17.530 --> 00:08:20.790
And he said, Kirk, "I don't just
want to do the illustrations.

00:08:20.790 --> 00:08:25.200
I want to have some say
in the font and the color

00:08:25.200 --> 00:08:27.970
and the cover and
the back cover.

00:08:27.970 --> 00:08:30.360
I don't want them just to
take it and do their thing.

00:08:30.360 --> 00:08:31.810
I want to have some input."

00:08:31.810 --> 00:08:33.200
I said, "Well, you've
gotta talk to the designer.

00:08:33.200 --> 00:08:34.789
I'm not sure she's
open to that."

00:08:34.789 --> 00:08:37.309
As it turns out, she
was open to that,

00:08:37.309 --> 00:08:38.990
and actually did a great job.

00:08:38.990 --> 00:08:45.570
But in any case, the
point being that while I

00:08:45.570 --> 00:08:47.660
was talking to Leighton,
and he was telling me

00:08:47.660 --> 00:08:51.470
that he had a larger
goal, he said, "So,

00:08:51.470 --> 00:08:53.580
just speaking
aesthetically, what do you

00:08:53.580 --> 00:08:55.840
want this book to look like?"

00:08:55.840 --> 00:08:58.920
And I said, "Well,
there's a book,

00:08:58.920 --> 00:09:01.860
the first edition of this
very famous marine biology

00:09:01.860 --> 00:09:06.380
tome that all fish geeks
know all about this book

00:09:06.380 --> 00:09:09.870
or all vertebrate geeks
know about this book."

00:09:09.870 --> 00:09:11.730
And I just assumed
that Leighton would not

00:09:11.730 --> 00:09:15.660
know this book because he's
not an outdoorsman kind of guy.

00:09:15.660 --> 00:09:18.984
He's more of just a
brilliantly talented artist,

00:09:18.984 --> 00:09:20.650
but I don't think of
him as a person who

00:09:20.650 --> 00:09:23.220
forages in the intertidal zone.

00:09:23.220 --> 00:09:26.302
So I didn't think he would know
about "Between Pacific Tides."

00:09:26.302 --> 00:09:28.760
And I said, "Well, the name of
the book is 'Between Pacific

00:09:28.760 --> 00:09:31.410
Tides.' And if you get a first
edition copy, I'll pay for it.

00:09:31.410 --> 00:09:33.960
I just want you to look at it
so you get a sense of the feel

00:09:33.960 --> 00:09:35.620
and the look of that book."

00:09:35.620 --> 00:09:38.140
And he goes, "That's strange,
because I'm holding a first

00:09:38.140 --> 00:09:42.410
edition copy of 'Between Pacific
Tides.' I've had it for, like,

00:09:42.410 --> 00:09:43.415
my entire life.

00:09:43.415 --> 00:09:47.620
It's like 35 years old,"
or however old Leighton is.

00:09:47.620 --> 00:09:49.370
"And it was sitting
right here on my desk.

00:09:49.370 --> 00:09:50.720
And that's actually
why I was calling you.

00:09:50.720 --> 00:09:53.011
I wanted to know if you wanted
the book to kind of look

00:09:53.011 --> 00:09:53.600
like that."

00:09:53.600 --> 00:09:56.340
And it was one of those
moments of synchronicity.

00:09:56.340 --> 00:09:58.730
But it gets weirder.

00:09:58.730 --> 00:10:01.325
And I said, "So Leighton,
you're not a forager.

00:10:01.325 --> 00:10:03.700
You're not a fisherman and
you're not a marine biologist.

00:10:03.700 --> 00:10:04.783
Why do you have that book?

00:10:04.783 --> 00:10:07.000
And why do you have a
first edition copy of it?"

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:10.410
And he said, "Well, I've been
meaning to tell you this,

00:10:10.410 --> 00:10:14.580
but did you know that my
grandfather, Richie Lovejoy,

00:10:14.580 --> 00:10:19.770
did all of the illustrations for
'Between Pacific Tides?' I said

00:10:19.770 --> 00:10:24.560
"No, I had no idea," which
is just really bizarre.

00:10:24.560 --> 00:10:26.780
And you know, when
things come together

00:10:26.780 --> 00:10:29.590
like that-- it was
sort of at that moment

00:10:29.590 --> 00:10:33.510
that-- I knew from the
start that Leighton

00:10:33.510 --> 00:10:34.530
was the guy for the job.

00:10:34.530 --> 00:10:37.420
But then that just kind
of cemented the deal.

00:10:37.420 --> 00:10:41.720
And so I gave Leighton,
in the back of the book,

00:10:41.720 --> 00:10:46.690
there's a little-- I love his--
he always remains incognito.

00:10:46.690 --> 00:10:48.710
He did a little sketch
in the back of the book,

00:10:48.710 --> 00:10:50.830
and he didn't want
our full visages.

00:10:50.830 --> 00:10:56.330
If you go back to page
257, he put a catfish

00:10:56.330 --> 00:10:58.360
in front of his face.

00:10:58.360 --> 00:11:03.130
Of course that catfish,
in Vietnam or somewhere

00:11:03.130 --> 00:11:07.960
in Southeast Asia, that catfish
is referred to as a lele.

00:11:07.960 --> 00:11:10.990
And that happens to be
Leighton's nickname.

00:11:10.990 --> 00:11:15.070
But on the last couple
pages, page 258, 259,

00:11:15.070 --> 00:11:17.610
I let Leighton tell the story
of his grandfather Richie

00:11:17.610 --> 00:11:21.970
Lovejoy, who was best friends
with Ed Ricketts and John

00:11:21.970 --> 00:11:23.872
Steinbeck.

00:11:23.872 --> 00:11:26.080
I want you to know that I'm
more proud of the editing

00:11:26.080 --> 00:11:28.510
that I did on these--
because this was six pages.

00:11:28.510 --> 00:11:30.510
Leighton is a little verbose.

00:11:30.510 --> 00:11:33.560
I cut him down to
a page and a half.

00:11:33.560 --> 00:11:35.360
I'm very proud of that.

00:11:35.360 --> 00:11:37.160
And he would be
happy about that too,

00:11:37.160 --> 00:11:40.170
because he kind of went
off on some tangents.

00:11:40.170 --> 00:11:41.765
He doesn't know
this, so hopefully he

00:11:41.765 --> 00:11:42.640
won't see this video.

