00:47:22.320 --> 00:47:22.605
KIRK LOMBARD: No.

00:47:22.605 --> 00:47:24.580
Well, I got into the
diving a little bit

00:47:24.580 --> 00:47:27.000
on the abalone section
too, more about

00:47:27.000 --> 00:47:30.010
how easy it is to kill
yourself when you do it,

00:47:30.010 --> 00:47:31.520
which almost happened to me.

00:47:31.520 --> 00:47:36.620
I wrote a whole thing about-- my
first abalone dive, I was new.

00:47:36.620 --> 00:47:38.690
My buddy took me out.

00:47:38.690 --> 00:47:41.410
And we went in and the
whole time I'm out there,

00:47:41.410 --> 00:47:44.340
I'm just like, man,
this is just sketchy.

00:47:44.340 --> 00:47:45.730
I just know this is sketchy.

00:47:45.730 --> 00:47:46.800
There's seals everywhere.

00:47:46.800 --> 00:47:48.280
And he's like, "You
don't have to worry

00:47:48.280 --> 00:47:49.260
about seals everywhere.

00:47:49.260 --> 00:47:52.480
What you got to worry about is
when they're out of the water."

00:47:52.480 --> 00:47:55.370
Literally 15 minutes later,
he's got his abalones,

00:47:55.370 --> 00:47:57.490
I'm still half drowning
trying to get the abalone

00:47:57.490 --> 00:47:58.680
to come up to the surface.

00:47:58.680 --> 00:48:01.930
All the seals are sitting on
the rocks, every one of them.

00:48:01.930 --> 00:48:03.780
There wasn't a single
one in the water.

00:48:03.780 --> 00:48:05.970
And his boat has
drifted 100 yards away.

00:48:05.970 --> 00:48:09.224
And I'm stuck in the
middle of this cove.

00:48:09.224 --> 00:48:11.420
And I start going like
this and he's waving back.

00:48:11.420 --> 00:48:13.350
He's not moving the boat.

00:48:13.350 --> 00:48:16.990
So I just-- I was like, OK.

00:48:16.990 --> 00:48:19.200
I got a flash.

00:48:19.200 --> 00:48:21.090
An abalone iron's
made out of steel,

00:48:21.090 --> 00:48:23.570
and it's flashing in the water.

00:48:23.570 --> 00:48:24.736
I got my big rubber thing.

00:48:24.736 --> 00:48:26.110
I got the thing
that measures it.

00:48:26.110 --> 00:48:27.318
That's flashing in the water.

00:48:27.318 --> 00:48:30.783
So flashing is something
that sharks really like.

00:48:30.783 --> 00:48:33.342
I had to start swimming.

00:48:33.342 --> 00:48:35.550
I'm like fuck this, I'm
going to do a Michael Phelps.

00:48:35.550 --> 00:48:38.130
I'm going to beat all
the known records man.

00:48:38.130 --> 00:48:39.150
I'm like, joosh, joosh.

00:48:39.150 --> 00:48:40.340
I get all the way
back to the boat.

00:48:40.340 --> 00:48:41.299
I'm like totally tired.

00:48:41.299 --> 00:48:42.256
I'm like, "You asshole.

00:48:42.256 --> 00:48:43.100
I can't believe you.

00:48:43.100 --> 00:48:43.800
Couldn't you come over?"

00:48:43.800 --> 00:48:44.490
And he's like, "I don't know.

00:48:44.490 --> 00:48:45.781
There's some fish biting here."

00:48:45.781 --> 00:48:47.240
He's fishing.

00:48:47.240 --> 00:48:49.850
I put my arm over the side
of the-- it's a Zodiac.

00:48:49.850 --> 00:48:52.350
We're in a 10 foot
inflatable Zodiac,

00:48:52.350 --> 00:48:55.600
which those are pretty rugged
boats, but 10 feet or 12 feet

00:48:55.600 --> 00:48:56.360
or something.

00:48:56.360 --> 00:48:58.027
And I put my arm over.

00:48:58.027 --> 00:48:59.110
I'm like trying to get up.

00:48:59.110 --> 00:48:59.962
I'm like ugh.

00:48:59.962 --> 00:49:01.920
I'm like, this is the
moment right here, right,

00:49:01.920 --> 00:49:04.360
because I got all
this stuff dangling.

00:49:04.360 --> 00:49:06.650
I have all my gear
dangling around my belt,

00:49:06.650 --> 00:49:08.470
you know, my legs
flapping in the water.

00:49:08.470 --> 00:49:11.150
It was like, this is where
he's going to freaking get me.

00:49:11.150 --> 00:49:13.500
Finally I get out of the water.

00:49:13.500 --> 00:49:14.520
I'm like OK.

00:49:14.520 --> 00:49:16.370
Finally I'm in the boat.

00:49:16.370 --> 00:49:20.560
And I look over at my
friend, and he's got his rod.

00:49:20.560 --> 00:49:22.610
And he's like, "Oh
man, I got one on,"

00:49:22.610 --> 00:49:26.850
because he was fishing
while I was swimming.

00:49:26.850 --> 00:49:29.350
And I looked kind of over,
and the water's very clear.

00:49:29.350 --> 00:49:30.180
And it's a lingcod.

00:49:30.180 --> 00:49:32.005
I can see that, and it's small.

00:49:32.005 --> 00:49:34.380
We call those shakers because
you shake them off the hook

00:49:34.380 --> 00:49:35.421
because they're so small.

00:49:35.421 --> 00:49:37.190
But he's bringing it up.

00:49:37.190 --> 00:49:40.910
And I'm kind of looking
at it in the water.

00:49:40.910 --> 00:49:43.830
And all of a sudden, underneath
the fish, there's just this,

00:49:43.830 --> 00:49:44.900
whoosh.

00:49:44.900 --> 00:49:46.905
Like the whole color of
the water just changed.

00:49:46.905 --> 00:49:48.880
And it went, whoosh.

00:49:48.880 --> 00:49:51.900
And we both went, "What
the fuck was that?"

00:49:51.900 --> 00:49:55.360
And he's like--
he's looking down.

00:49:55.360 --> 00:49:56.382
He's like, huh?

00:49:56.382 --> 00:49:57.840
And he starts
reeling up like this.

00:49:57.840 --> 00:49:59.310
And then just out
of nowhere, man, I

00:49:59.310 --> 00:50:01.101
don't even know where
this thing came from.

00:50:01.101 --> 00:50:02.840
There's a 12 foot
great white shark

00:50:02.840 --> 00:50:05.566
coming up underneath this
fish with its mouth like this.

00:50:05.566 --> 00:50:07.190
And we're in this
little fricking boat.

00:50:07.190 --> 00:50:10.630
Dude, I'm sitting like
this, and it's there.

00:50:10.630 --> 00:50:12.660
Like if I wanted to put
my arm down its mouth

00:50:12.660 --> 00:50:16.020
for some insane reason,
I could have done that.

00:50:16.020 --> 00:50:17.840
I just kind of
looked over the side.

00:50:17.840 --> 00:50:19.900
I still had one of
my flippers on man.

00:50:19.900 --> 00:50:22.100
I'm like one flipper
on, one flipper off.

00:50:22.100 --> 00:50:24.890
And then I just
started screaming.

00:50:24.890 --> 00:50:31.160
And my friend, you know, he's
sort of an unorthodox guy.

00:50:31.160 --> 00:50:33.901
So my feeling, at that
moment, the thing's

00:50:33.901 --> 00:50:35.400
coming up after the
fish that you're

00:50:35.400 --> 00:50:37.890
reeling in, just get the
fucking thing out of the water.

00:50:37.890 --> 00:50:39.513
Let's get out of here, you know?

00:50:39.513 --> 00:50:41.596
But he's kind of like,
just kind of sitting there.

00:50:41.596 --> 00:50:42.860
He's like oh.

00:50:42.860 --> 00:50:47.440
He would have the fish on
the surface, like lingering

00:50:47.440 --> 00:50:50.746
to sort of tease the animal.

00:50:50.746 --> 00:50:52.370
And I was like, "Get
it out the water!"

00:50:52.370 --> 00:50:55.220
And he goes OK, and vroom,
vroom, and we took off

00:50:55.220 --> 00:50:56.580
and we left it.

00:50:56.580 --> 00:51:01.230
And I often regret, actually--
because it was so close to us

00:51:01.230 --> 00:51:02.890
and it circled us.

00:51:02.890 --> 00:51:06.856
And I regret that my instinct
was to grab for my phone

00:51:06.856 --> 00:51:08.730
and get some video
footage of this thing that

00:51:08.730 --> 00:51:10.660
was right next to us.

00:51:10.660 --> 00:51:14.410
And in doing that-- I mean,
how often you going to be that

00:51:14.410 --> 00:51:15.630
close to a great white shark?

00:51:15.630 --> 00:51:18.550
I mean, I've seen them in
fishing boats where they're

00:51:18.550 --> 00:51:20.820
like over there or over there.

00:51:20.820 --> 00:51:24.130
But in a little Zodiac
where it's right-- like,

00:51:24.130 --> 00:51:27.630
you could grab its dorsal fin.

00:51:27.630 --> 00:51:30.020
And instead of
experiencing the moment,

00:51:30.020 --> 00:51:31.370
I was looking for my phone.

00:51:31.370 --> 00:51:33.310
So I really wish that
I hadn't done that.

00:51:33.310 --> 00:51:35.560
I really wish that I had
just been present and watched

00:51:35.560 --> 00:51:37.770
that thing all the
way around the boat.

00:51:37.770 --> 00:51:39.350
But I mean, I saw
it close enough.

00:51:39.350 --> 00:51:41.910
But the upshot of this
was, of course, it

00:51:41.910 --> 00:51:46.445
didn't encourage me to continue
my abalone diving career.

00:51:46.445 --> 00:51:49.040
[LAUGHTER]

00:51:49.040 --> 00:51:53.360
So I'm sort of a wimp
when it comes to that.

00:51:53.360 --> 00:51:57.600
When I go get abalones, I do
a thing called shore picking,

00:51:57.600 --> 00:51:59.100
which is also really dangerous.

00:51:59.100 --> 00:52:00.558
A lot of people
drown short picking

00:52:00.558 --> 00:52:04.590
because you're in water up to
here, so you dive down to go,

00:52:04.590 --> 00:52:06.790
and you're kind of under a rock.

00:52:06.790 --> 00:52:08.620
And you can get stuck.

00:52:08.620 --> 00:52:10.200
And you can drown
in that much water

00:52:10.200 --> 00:52:12.740
as easily as you can in 20 feet.

00:52:12.740 --> 00:52:19.080
So in any case, that story's in
there, a longer version of it.

